article.description: Kevin Johnson and Jason Parker had 18 points apiece, and No. 22 Tulsa overcame 29 by Reggie Borges to defeat crosstown rival Oral Roberts 90-80 Thursday night.
article.headline: Golden rivalry: Hurricane gets best of Eagles
article.linkText: Golden rivalry: Hurricane gets best of Eagles
article.story:
TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- Tulsa finally found an opponent it can bully inside.

Kevin Johnson and Jason Parker had 18 points apiece as No. 22 Tulsa defeated crosstown rival Oral Roberts 90-80 Thursday night.
 
Jarius Glenn and Dante Swanson had four points each in a late 12-3 run Tulsa (6-1) used to put the game out of reach. It was Tulsa's third straight win over the Golden Eagles.

"I thought in the second half we just played tremendous,'' Tulsa coach John Phillips said. "We rebounded. We guarded. We did everything we've been trying to get accomplished.''

Reggie Borges scored 29 points and had seven rebounds for Oral Roberts (6-2). It was an unusually lopsided game in the series. Tulsa needed overtime to win the past two seasons.

"I gave up a lot of offensive rebounds and made too many turnovers,'' Borges said. "I don't take anything positive from this.''

Glenn, starting for the injured Antonio Reed, finished with 17 points. Swanson added 16 as Tulsa claimed the 39th Mayor's Cup, the trophy given to the game's winner. Johnson also had eight rebounds.

Glenn's tip-in with 3:57 remaining capped Tulsa's definitive
run, giving the Golden Hurricane their largest lead at 82-65. Tulsa
then hit 8-for-12 free throws -- with Parker making all six of his
attempts -- in the final 2:12 to seal the victory.

"I was tired of hearing all the buzz about Oral Roberts,''
Glenn said. "We wanted to come out and put them away early.''

Tulsa took the lead for good with a 12-3 run to close the first
half. Marcus Ledoux scored seven points in the spurt, including a
dunk on an alley-oop pass from Swanson that put the Golden
Hurricane ahead 47-39.

The Golden Eagles shot 67 percent in the first half but still trailed 47-42 at the break after Luke Spencer-Gardner's 3-pointer with time expiring ended Tulsa's run. Tulsa shot 65 percent in the first half.

"I thought the game slipped away from us the last few minutes of the first half,'' Oral Roberts coach Scott Sutton said. "The second half we had to play catch-up and when you get outrebounded 37-19 you're not going to win many games.''

Oral Roberts never got closer than four points in the second
half, pulling to 58-54 on a basket by Tyrone Tiggs with 13:18 left.
But Johnson hit a 3 to widen Tulsa's lead.

Fourteen of Tulsa's rebounds came off the offensive backboards, a stark reversal from their loss last week to No. 19 Kansas. The Jayhawks got 19 offensive rebounds in that game.

"I think we've got a chance to be a really good defensive team,
but we were wasting that effort by not rebounding,'' Phillips said.
